    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-09-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-09-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d241">
                <head>241. Telegram 175047 From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss>
                    to the <gloss type="to">Mission in Geneva</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d241fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–1973, DEF 18–3 Switz
                        (GE). Confidential; Immediate. Repeated immediate to All <gloss
                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> Capitals, <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                            >USUN</gloss>, Moscow, Tokyo, and USDel <gloss target="#t_SALT1"
                            >SALT</gloss> V. Drafted by Rodes (<gloss target="#t_ACDAIR1"
                            >ACDA/IR</gloss>); cleared in <gloss target="#t_PM1">PM</gloss>/DCA,
                            <gloss target="#t_DOD1">DOD</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_ISA1">ISA</gloss>,
                            <gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>/RPM, <gloss target="#t_IO1"
                            >IO</gloss>/UNP, <gloss target="#t_L1">L</gloss>, the White House,
                            <gloss target="#t_ACDAIR1">ACDA/IR</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_ACDA1"
                            >ACDA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_GC1">GC</gloss>; and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_FPJ1">Farley</persName>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d241fn2">The telegram transmitted
                        instructions for the final text of the draft convention on biological
                        weapons.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1971-09-23"
                        >September 23, 1971</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CCD1">CCD</gloss>: Negotiation of <gloss target="#t_BW1"
                            >BW</gloss> Convention</item>
                </list>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>REF:</head>
                    <item>A. Geneva 3844</item>
                    <item>B. Geneva 3849</item>
                    <item>C. Geneva 3850</item>
                    <item>D. Geneva 3851</item>
                    <item>E. Geneva 3852</item>
                    <item>F. Geneva 4036</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>We are prepared to accept changes in text of August 5 draft convention as
                        reported reftels, subject to comments in para 3 below.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>We appreciate efforts of Del to arrive at draft which would appear
                        generally acceptable at <gloss target="#t_CCD1">CCD</gloss> and at <gloss
                            target="#t_UNGA1">UNGA</gloss>. We believe some additions will be
                        particularly acceptable <pb facs="d241-02" n="2" xml:id="d241-02"/> to our
                        allies (e.g., additions to Articles I and V) while new language proposed by
                        non-aligned for preamble and operative Articles VIII and IX should increase
                        support for Convention.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>a. We prefer maintain August 5 version preambular para 1. If, however, in
                            judgment of Del, it would not be possible to achieve agreement on <gloss
                                target="#t_BW1">BW</gloss> treaty at this <gloss target="#t_CCD1"
                                >CCD</gloss> session without suggested changes—and we highly value
                            Del efforts in inserting reference to “effective measures”—Del is
                            authorized to agree to proposed changes.</p>
                        <p>b. We favor inclusion of optional article on <gloss target="#t_BW1"
                                >BW</gloss> assistance (para 13, reftel D) if, in light of further
                            consultations with Sovs and other dels, <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                >US</gloss> Del believes this would enhance overall support for
                            treaty. If article included <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> Del should
                            make clear our understanding that it refers to humanitarian
                            assistance.</p>
                        <pb facs="d241-03" n="3" xml:id="d241-03"/>
                        <p>c. We consider preambular para 4 of proposed text an improvement, but we
                            continue to be able to accept August 5 version.</p>
                        <p>d. Del should not raise question of insertion word “comprehensive” in
                            preambular para 8 of proposed text (para 7, reftel C), particularly in
                            light of latest Soviet change in this para (see 3e below.)</p>
                        <p>e. We can also accept the two additional changes pip proposed by Soviets
                            (reftel F): that is, (1) deletion of word, “appropriate” in optional
                            article on assistance; and (2) deletion of words “and bacteriological
                            (biological)” together with the insertion word “also” in preambular
                            paragraph 8 of proposed text, so that revised para would read:
                            “Recognizing that an agreement on the prohibition of bacteriological
                            (biological) and toxin weapons represents a first possible step towards
                            the achievement of agreement on effective measures also <pb
                                facs="d241-04" n="4" xml:id="d241-04"/> for prohibition of the
                            development, production and stockpiling of chemical weapons, and
                            determined to continue negotiations to that end.”</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>FOR USNATO, ALL <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> CAPITALS AND
                        AMEMBASSY TOKYO: Consultations with our <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                            >NATO</gloss> allies and Japan on new language should begin soonest
                        following receipt instructions which being sent septel.</item>
                </list>
                <p>END</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
